This is what the implementation will look like in MutableCollection:
default MutableCollection<T> with(T element)
{
    this.add(element);
    return this;
}

Duplicating the implementation looks like this:
@Override
default MutableList<T> with(T element)
{
    this.add(element);
    return this;
}

Or calling the super default implementation:
@Override
default MutableList<T> with(T element)
{
    MutableCollection.super.with(element);
    return this;
}

The question I have is what is the benefit of pulling up the implementation to MutableCollection if we are not going to use the pulled up implementation? This could create an uncovered or difficult to cover code path. We could leave it abstract in MutableCollection and enforce it being overridden at leaf interfaces. Thoughts?

